VITE_BLOG='[{"id":"agile-scrum-ai-pm","title":"How to Use Agile & Scrum in AI Product Management","subtitle":"Adapting traditional methodologies for the unique challenges of AI product development","excerpt":"<h2>Why Agile is a Good Fit for AI Projects</h2><p>AI projects involve uncertainty, evolving requirements, and experimental research. Agile helps by offering:</p><ul><li><strong>Iterative development:</strong> Frequent model updates and experiments.</li><li><strong>Stakeholder feedback:</strong> Aligns AI outputs with business needs.</li><li><strong>Early delivery:</strong> Deliver MVPs to collect data or validate ideas.</li><li><strong>Risk management:</strong> De-risk complex model development in small increments.</li></ul><h2>Scrum Roles Adapted for AI Teams</h2><p>Scrum roles reimagined for AI product teams:</p><table border="1" cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0"><thead><tr><th>Scrum Role</th><th>AI Team Equivalent</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Product Owner</strong></td><td>Defines backlog, prioritizes experiments, bridges business and data science.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Scrum Master</strong></td><td>Facilitates agile rituals, removes blockers, fosters collaboration.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Development Team</strong></td><td>Comprises data scientists, ML engineers, backend/frontend devs, and analysts.</td></tr></tbody></table><h2>Scrum in AI Product Development</h2><p>Scrum in AI should adapt for model experimentation and data exploration:</p><ol><li><strong>Sprint Planning:</strong> Identify backlog items like preprocessing, model training, etc.</li><li><strong>Daily Stand-ups:</strong> Discuss blockers like low data quality or training issues.</li><li><strong>Sprint Reviews:</strong> Demo metrics, model insights, or feature outputs.</li><li><strong>Retrospectives:</strong> Improve based on data drift, model failure, or deployment delays.</li></ol><h2>Managing AI Backlogs</h2><p>AI backlogs should include research, uncertainty handling, and model tasks:</p><ul><li>Include <strong>spikes</strong> for research or unknowns.</li><li>Define <strong>clear acceptance criteria</strong> like accuracy thresholds.</li><li>Use <strong>experimentation tickets</strong> for model comparisons.</li></ul><h2>Sample Sprint Backlog</h2><table border="1" cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0"><thead><tr><th>Task</th><th>Type</th><th>Owner</th><th>Status</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Collect user clickstream data</td><td>Data</td><td>Data Engineer</td><td>In Progress</td></tr><tr><td>Train classification model</td><td>ML</td><td>ML Engineer</td><td>To Do</td></tr><tr><td>Hyperparameter tuning</td><td>Experiment</td><td>ML Engineer</td><td>To Do</td></tr><tr><td>Build prediction UI</td><td>Frontend</td><td>Web Dev</td><td>Done</td></tr></tbody></table><h2>Challenges & Solutions</h2><table border="1" cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0"><thead><tr><th>Challenge</th><th>Solution</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Unclear model KPIs</td><td>Define business-aligned metrics like precision, recall.</td></tr><tr><td>Variable data quality</td><td>Include data validation and audits in sprints.</td></tr><tr><td>Slow training times</td><td>Plan experiments around compute schedules.</td></tr><tr><td>Cross-functional gaps</td><td>Encourage communication via daily standups and shared docs.</td></tr></tbody></table><h2>Best Practices</h2><ul><li><strong>Align vision:</strong> Connect sprint tasks to AI goals.</li><li><strong>Involve stakeholders:</strong> Validate outputs regularly.</li><li><strong>Track experiments:</strong> Use MLflow or Weights & Biases.</li><li><strong>Focus on explainability:</strong> Integrate SHAP, LIME early on.</li></ul><h2>Conclusion</h2><p>Agile and Scrum provide adaptable, iterative frameworks to build, test, and scale AI products. By tailoring ceremonies and roles, teams can better manage complexity, improve collaboration, and deliver smarter outcomes.</p>
